        "heading_3zUj3k": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Know your flow!"
          }
        },
        "description_iMjCqF": {
          "type": "description",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Our period panties are designed to absorb liquid equivalent to up to 5 regular tampons or pads (25 ml) and can be worn for up to 12 hours. How long they last depends on the amount of fluid and the viscosity of the fluid.</p>"
          }
        },
        "description_HaCbwR": {
          "type": "description",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>The average menstrual flow is 30–40 ml over a full cycle, spread over 5–7 days — roughly the size of a small espresso cup. Light bleeding is typically 10–30 ml per cycle, while heavy bleeding is anything above 60–80 ml per cycle. Around 90% of bleeding usually occurs during the first three days, with a peak on day two.</p>"
          }
        },
        "description_FQm6pi": {
          "type": "description",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>The viscosity of the fluid also plays an important role. Think of the difference between water, which has low viscosity, and honey, which has high viscosity. Women experience different levels of viscosity in menstrual flow. The higher the viscosity, the easier it is for period panties to absorb the fluid. With low viscosity and heavy bleeding early in the cycle, the underwear may need to be changed more often than every 12 hours. Toward the end of the cycle, they will typically last longer than 12 hours.</p>"
          }
        },
        "description_3qiH6x": {
          "type": "description",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>It’s important to get to know your own flow — know your flow. We recommend trying the underwear at home first to understand how and when to change them. If you feel unsure at the beginning, you can also use period panties together with a menstrual cup or tampon.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
